item.label: Basilar sulcus
item.name: Basilar sulcus
item.description: The basilar sulcus is a midline groove on the ventral or anterior aspect of the basilar portion of the pons. The basilar artery lies within this sulcus.

item.label: Midbrain, tectum
item.name: Midbrain, tectum
item.description: The tectum is that portion of the midbrain located above the cerebral aqueduct.  It includes the superior and inferior colliculi which are AKA the quadrigeminal bodies.

item.label: Midbrain, tegmentum
item.name: Midbrain, tegmentum
item.description: The tegmentum is that portion of the midbrain that lies between the cerebral aqueduct and the crus cerebri.  It includes the major ascending sensory tracts (medial lemniscus, spinothalamic), the red nucleus and the substantia nigra.

item.label: Pons, basilar
item.name: Pons, basilar
item.description: The basilar pons is AKA the basal pons. It is the ventral portion of the pons that includes the following important elements that are primarily involved in motor control: corticospinal, corticobulbar, corticospinal and pontocerebellar tracts plus the pontine nuclei. Thus, it serves as a conduit for descending motor pathways from cerebral cortex to the pons, medulla and spinal cord. In addition, it connects the cerebral cortex with the cerebellum via synapses of the corticopontine fibers on pontine nuclei that then give origin to the pontocerebellar fibers which terminate in cerebellum.

item.label: Inferior colliculus
item.name: Inferior colliculus
item.description: The inferior colliculi are paired rounded structures on the superior surface of the caudal midbrain formed by the paired nuclei of the inferior colliculus.  Along with the paired superior colliculi in the rostral midbrain, they form the tectum or roof of the midbrain and are collectively referred to as the corpora quadrigemina. The inferior colliculus is an important synapse in the auditory pathway, receiving auditory input from the lateral lemniscus and sending its output via the brachium of the inferior colliculus to synapse in the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Inferior colliculus, nucleus
item.name: Inferior colliculus, nucleus
item.description: The nuclei that make up the inferior colliculi receive auditory input via the lateral lemniscus and project or send their output to the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus via the brachium of the inferior colliculus.

item.label: Periaqueductal gray matter
item.name: Periaqueductal gray matter
item.description: Periaqueductal gray matter is the area of gray matter surrounding the cerebral aqueduct of the midbrain. Some of the neurons in this area are part of a descending analgesic pathway that relays in the nucleus raphe magnus of the medulla and subsequently blocks pain at the level of the dorsal horn.

item.label: Pontine nuclei
item.name: Pontine nuclei
item.description: The pontine nuclei are a large number of small nuclei located in the basilar portion of the pons. They are scattered among many nerve fibers in this area. They receive input from the ipsilateral cerebral cortex via corticopontine fibers that travel to the pons via the internal capsule and cerebral crus; they give origin to pontocerebellar fibers whose axons cross the midline and enter the cerebellum contralateral to their origin

item.label: Trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus
item.name: Trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus
item.description: The trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus is the portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei located in the midbrain. It contains the cell bodies of first-order primary afferents that carry proprioceptive information from the muscles of mastication and other oral mechanoreceptors. The peripheral processes of these neurons travel in the mandibular root of the trigeminal nerve and serve as the afferent limb of the jaw jerk reflex. The central processes of these neurons synapse on the trigeminal motor nucleus which provides the efferent limb of the jaw jerk reflex.

item.label: Corticospinal, -bulbar, pontine trs
item.name: Corticospinal, -bulbar, pontine trs
item.description: These descending motor tracts originate in the cerebral cortex and then travel through the posterior limb of the internal capsule, the cerebral crus of the midbrain, the basilar portion of the pons and the pyramids of the medulla.  Sometimes this group of tracts is referred to as the pyramidal tract or system.  It includes the corticospinal, corticobulbar and corticopontine tracts.  The corticopontine fibers terminate at the level of the pons; therefore, the pyramids contain only corticospinal and corticobulbar fibers while only the corticospinal fibers continue into the spinal cord.  There are other subcortical descending motor tracts (reticulospinal and vestibulospinal) that originate in the reticular formation and vestibular nuclei of the brain stem.

item.label: Inferior colliculus, brachium
item.name: Inferior colliculus, brachium
item.description: The brachium of the inferior colliculus is AKA the inferior brachium. It is a band of nerve fibers carrying auditory input from the inferior colliculus of the midbrain to the medial geniculate nucleus of the thalamus. It is clearly visible grossly on the lateral aspect of the midbrain.

item.label: Inferior colliculus, commissure
item.name: Inferior colliculus, commissure
item.description: The commissure of the inferior colliculus consists of nerve fibers that cross the midline in the caudal aspect of the tectum, connecting the nuclei of the inferior colliculus.

item.label: Lateral lemniscus
item.name: Lateral lemniscus
item.description: The lateral lemniscus is a portion of the auditory pathway that transmits auditory information from the ipsilateral and contralateral (primarily) cochlear nuclei and superior olivary nuclei to the nucleus of the inferior colliculus.

item.label: Medial lemniscus
item.name: Medial lemniscus
item.description: The medial lemniscus is the primary ascending tract carrying tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive information from the body through the brainstem. Cells of origin are in the contralateral cuneate and gracile nuclei; termination is in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus of the thalamus. Comparable input from the head is carried in trigeminothalamic tract fibers that accompany the medial lemniscus but terminate in the ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.description: The medial longitudinal fasciculus is an important ascending fiber bundle involved in the coordination of horizontal eye movements through its origin in the vestibular nuclei and termination in the oculomotor and abducens nuclei. It is an important component of the VOR (vestibulo-ocular) reflex. A descending component of this tract (AKA medial vestibulospinal tract) travels to cervical levels of the cord and is involved in turning of the head in response to vestibular stimulation.

item.label: Middle cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Middle cerebellar peduncle
item.description: The middle cerebellar peduncle consists exclusively of pontocerebellar tract fibers that take their origin from pontine nuclei in the contralateral basilar pons. Thus, it carries afferent information to cerebellum from the contralateral cerebral cortex via the corticopontine to pontine nuclei to pontocerebellar tract.

item.label: Pontocerebellar fibers
item.name: Pontocerebellar fibers
item.description: The pontine nuclei in the basal or basilar portion of the pons are the origin of the pontocerebellar tract. The tract crosses the midline at the level of the pons to travel as the middle cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the cerebellum contralateral to the cell bodies of origin.

item.label: Spinothalamic tract
item.name: Spinothalamic tract
item.description: The spinothalamic tract is primarily responsible for transmitting nociceptive (pain) and temperature information from the body. Small diameter primary afferents (first order neurons) bring the pain and temperature information into the ipsilateral dorsal horn where they synapse on the cells of origin of the spinothalamic tract. The second order neurons in the dorsal horn send their axons across the midline in the ventral white commissure so that the spinothalmamic tract ascends in the anterolateral portion of the spinal cord contralateral to the side of input of the information. This tract terminates in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus (VPL) of thalamus. From this thalamic nucleus, the information is carried to the primary somatosensory cerebral cortex where the sensation is consciously perceived.

item.label: Superior cerebellar peduncle decussation
item.name: Superior cerebellar peduncle decussation
item.description: A major portion of the output from the cerebellum travels in the superior cerebellar peduncles.  As these paired peduncles travel rostrally toward the midbrain, they cross the midline within the tegmentum of the caudal midbrain in what is termed the decussation of the superior cerebellar peduncle.

item.label: Trigeminal mesencephalic tract
item.name: Trigeminal mesencephalic tract
item.description: The trigeminal mesencephalic tract is composed of the processes of the first-order primary afferent neurons in the adjacent trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus.  Those neurons have a 'peripheral' branch that travels with the mandibular root of the trigeminal nerve to innervate muscle spindles in the muscles of mastication and other oral mechanoreceptors.  The 'central' branch of these neurons terminates centrally, particularly in the trigeminal motor nucleus, as part of the jaw jerk reflex.

item.label: Trigeminothalamic tract
item.name: Trigeminothalamic tract
item.description: The trigeminothalamic tract originates in the trigeminal spinal nucleus and the trigeminal main sensory nucleus and terminates in the ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Trigeminal nerve
item.name: Trigeminal nerve
item.description: The fifth or trigeminal cranial nerve enters/exits the brain stem through the basilar portion of the pons. It provides somatosensory innervation to the head via its ophthalmic, maxillary and mandibular roots which converge upon the trigeminal ganglion and then form a massive sensory root entering the brainstem. It provides motor innervation to the muscles derived from the first branchial arch (muscles of mastication, tensor tympani, anterior belly of diagastric, tensor veli palatini and mylohyoid) via a smaller motor root that distributes with the mandibular sensory root.

item.label: Trigeminal mesencephalic tract
item.name: Trigeminal mesencephalic tract_1
item.description: The trigeminal mesencephalic tract is composed of the processes of the first-order primary afferent neurons in the adjacent trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus.  Those neurons have a 'peripheral' branch that travels with the mandibular root of the trigeminal nerve to innervate muscle spindles in the muscles of mastication and other oral mechanoreceptors.  The 'central' branch of these neurons terminates centrally, particularly in the trigeminal motor nucleus, as part of the jaw jerk reflex.

item.label: Trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus
item.name: Trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus_1
item.description: The trigeminal mesencephalic nucleus is the portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei located in the midbrain. It contains the cell bodies of first-order primary afferents that carry proprioceptive information from the muscles of mastication and other oral mechanoreceptors. The peripheral processes of these neurons travel in the mandibular root of the trigeminal nerve and serve as the afferent limb of the jaw jerk reflex. The central processes of these neurons synapse on the trigeminal motor nucleus which provides the efferent limb of the jaw jerk reflex.

item.label: Trochlear nerve
item.name: Trochlear nerve
item.description: The fourth or trochlear cranial nerve innervates the superior oblique muscle of the contralateral eye. It is the only cranial nerve to exit the dorsal aspect of the brainstem. This location is just caudal to the inferior colliculi of the midbrain.

item.label: Trochlear nucleus
item.name: Trochlear nucleus
item.description: This trochlear nucleus contains the lower motor neurons of the trochlear nerve. It is located in the midbrain at the level of the inferior colliculi. On a cross section of the midbrain, it is located at the inferior aspect of the periaqueductal gray matter. The nerve fibers exit the nucleus, encircle the cerebral aqueduct, decussate in the superior medullary velum prior to their exit immediately caudal to the inferior colliculi.

item.label: Cerebral aqueduct
item.name: Cerebral aqueduct
item.description: The cerebral aqueduct is AKA the cerebral aqueduct of Sylvius.  It is a narrow channel within the midbrain through which cerebrospinal fluid flows from the third ventricle into the fourth ventricle.
